        <section class="prose mt-8">
          <h2>How this hours calculator works</h2>
          <p>This tool combines three powerful time calculators in one:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Quick difference</strong> – find hours between two times, including overnight shifts.</li>
            <li><strong>Add / subtract hours</strong> – add or subtract hours and minutes from a base time.</li>
            <li><strong>Timesheet / work hours</strong> – track daily work hours with breaks, overtime and export.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>1. Calculating hours between two times</h3>
          <p>To compute the duration between a start time and an end time, the calculator:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>Converts each time to minutes since midnight:
              <span class="formula-box"><code>totalMinutes = hours × 60 + minutes</code></span>
            </li>
            <li>Computes the raw difference:
              <span class="formula-box"><code>diffMinutes = endMinutes − startMinutes</code></span>
            </li>
            <li>If the period crosses midnight, it adds 24 hours:
              <span class="formula-box"><code>if crossesMidnight and diffMinutes &lt; 0 then diffMinutes += 24 × 60</code></span>
            </li>
            <li>Converts back to hours and minutes:
              <span class="formula-box"><code>hours = floor(diffMinutes / 60)</code><br><code>minutes = diffMinutes mod 60</code></span>
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>The same duration is also shown as <strong>decimal hours</strong>:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <code>decimalHours = diffMinutes / 60</code>
          </div>

          <h3>2. Adding or subtracting hours</h3>
          <p>When you add or subtract time, the calculator converts everything to minutes, applies the operation, then converts back:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <code>baseMinutes = baseHours × 60 + baseMinutes</code><br>
            <code>deltaMinutes = deltaHours × 60 + deltaMinutes</code><br>
            <code>resultMinutes = baseMinutes ± deltaMinutes</code><br>
            <code>resultHours = floor(resultMinutes / 60)</code><br>
            <code>resultMins = resultMinutes mod 60</code>
          </div>
          <p>If the result is negative, it is still displayed correctly with a minus sign.</p>

          <h3>3. Work hours, breaks and overtime</h3>
          <p>In timesheet mode, each row represents one workday:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Gross time</strong> = time between start and end (with optional midnight crossing).</li>
            <li><strong>Net time</strong> = gross time − unpaid break minutes.</li>
            <li><strong>Daily overtime</strong> (optional) = max(0, net time − daily threshold).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Weekly overtime is calculated after summing all net hours:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <code>totalNetHours = Σ netHoursPerDay</code><br>
            <code>weeklyOvertime = max(0, totalNetHours − weeklyThreshold)</code>
          </div>

          <h2>Typical use cases</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Payroll and timesheets</strong> – track weekly hours, breaks and overtime.</li>
            <li><strong>Freelancers</strong> – log billable hours per client or project.</li>
            <li><strong>Shift workers</strong> – handle overnight shifts and rotating schedules.</li>
            <li><strong>Study or practice time</strong> – add up hours spent on tasks across days.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>FAQ</h2>

          <h3>Can I use 12‑hour times with AM/PM?</h3>
          <p>Yes. In quick difference mode you can switch between 24‑hour and 12‑hour formats. Internally the calculator always converts to 24‑hour time to avoid mistakes.</p>

          <h3>How accurate is the hours calculator?</h3>
          <p>All calculations are done in minutes and then converted to hours with up to two decimal places. There is no rounding until the final display, so results are accurate enough for payroll and billing.</p>

          <h3>What about lunch breaks and short pauses?</h3>
          <p>Enter the total unpaid break time for the day in minutes (for example, 30 for lunch plus 15 for a coffee break = 45). The calculator subtracts this from your shift duration to give net working time.</p>

          <h3>Is my data stored anywhere?</h3>
          <p>No. All calculations run in your browser. Nothing is sent to a server, and refreshing the page will clear your entries.</p>
        </section>
